Investment Title: FEMA - Integrated Public Alert & Warning System (IPAWS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: EAS Primary Entry Point (PEP) Expansion program is a resilient capability for the President to alert and warn citizens in times of national crisis. It can also be used by local authorities to provide local life-saving information during a crisis. PEP stations are commercial radio stations with additional FEMA-supplied capabilities that allow stations to operate and broadcast alert and warning messages under all-hazards. The IPAWS Program is expanding the number of PEP radio stations to provide direct coverage to 90% of the U.S. population.  The PEP expansion installs FEMA equipment into an existing commercial radio station.

Investment Title: FEMA - Integrated Public Alert & Warning System (IPAWS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: EAS Primary Entry Point (PEP) Modernization project is a resilient capability for the President to alert and warn citizens in times of national crisis. It can also be used by local authorities to provide local life-saving information during a crisis. PEP stations are commercial radio stations with additional FEMA-supplied capabilities that allow stations to operate and broadcast alert and warning messages under all-hazards. The IPAWS Program is modernizing legacy PEP stations with retrofitted fuel systems, all-hazard protection capabilities, and redundant communications equipment to make Legacy PEP stations more resilient.

Investment Title: FEMA - Integrated Public Alert & Warning System (IPAWS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: IPAWS-OPEN is an application and data center infrastructure that provides alert aggregation, authentication, and dissemination to multiple communication media. Communication media includes radio via the EAS, cellular phones via the Commercial Mobile Alert System (CMAS), NOAA All Hazards Radio, TV, Internet, and social media services. This project provides updates to the system to increase capability and useability.

Investment Title: FEMA - Integrated Public Alert & Warning System (IPAWS)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: EAS Primary Entry Point (PEP) Operations and Maintenance program is a resilient capability for the President to alert and warn citizens in times of national crisis. It can also be used by local authorities to provide local life-saving information during a crisis. PEP stations are commercial radio stations with additional FEMA-supplied capabilities that allow stations to operate and broadcast alert and warning messages under all-hazards. The IPAWS program will provide annual and as needed operations and maintenance, including operating system upgrades, technology refreshes, and security patch implementation in addition to physical infrastructure maintenance on the PEP stations to make PEP stations more resilient and warn citizens in times of national crisis. It can also be used by local authorities to provide local life-saving information during a crisis. PEP stations are commercial radio stations with additional FEMA-supplied capabilities that allow stations to operate and broadcast alert and warning messages under all-hazards. The IPAWS program will provide annual and as needed operations and maintenance on the PEP stations to make PEP stations more resilient.

This project is to upgrade and increase the Land Mobile Radio (LMR) system exponentially in support of the CBP agents and officers in the Houlton sector.  The project will bring the system into compliance with the NTIA Project 25(P25) narrow band standard. In addition, this will make the system Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) encryption capable, providing officers and agents with improved coverage, encryption and reliability.

This project is to upgrade and increase the Land Mobile Radio (LMR) system exponentially in support of the CBP agents and officers El Paso Focus Area.   This project will provide enhancements and improved operational capabilities to LMR systems for CBP personnel, OBP, OFO, and OAM in the ELP Focus Area. The Modernized P25 LMR system will provide improved communications to include compliance with the NTIA narrowband mandate, promoting interoperability with the use of standards, provide secure, advanced encryption communications, OTAR, and increased capacity .
The Rio Grande Valley (RGV) Texas Project is a Project 25 (P25) land mobile radio (LMR) tactical communications modernization system, sponsored by the Tactical Communications.

Digital In Place is a capstone project with the goal of replacing remaining legacy analog equipment not covered in the three Houlton, El Paso, and Rio Grande Valley sectors with P25 compliant equipment. The project will bring the remaining sectors into compliance with the NTIA Project 25(P25) narrow band standard. In addition, this will make the system Advanced Encryption Standard (AES)capable, providing officers and agents with improved encryption and reliability. While the three focus areas upgrade and improve coverage, the Cap-Stone DIP project will bring the remaining infrastructure to a common baseline at a cost less than the three focus areas combined.

Release 1 will develop and deploy the foundation of the Core Case Management functionality and infrastructure. It will allow special agents to begin conducting basic case management functions such as initiating cases, entering and querying Subject Records, and conducting Reports of Investigation (ROI). The ICE TECS Modernization system will synchronize data with the legacy TECS mainframe for Release 1 functionality, which will continue to serve as the System of Record.

Development and implementation of training, communications, and change management activities to support the modernized TECS system.
Misson Support and monitoring/oversight of the development of the TECS Modernization program.

The Windows 7 Operational Test and Evaluation (OTE) will test Windows 7/Office 2010, the latest operating system (OS) and office suite in the Microsoft series, and replace the existing Microsoft Windows XP and legacy operating systems, which are near the end of their life cycle. The purpose of this project is to Engineer, Test, and Deploy a standard CBP image, based on the Windows 7 operating system. In addition, bring CBP in compliance with Office of Management and Budget (OMB) implementation of the United States Government Configuration Baseline (USGCB), as outlined in OMB mandates M07-11 and M08-22 regarding standard security configurations.

Seeks to automate all information exchange between Trade, CBP and over 50 PGAs during the cargo importation, review and release process.  ITDS includes the Document Image System, PGA Interoperability Framework, and Support for the Standardized PGA Message Set.

During this project capabilities will be created for Cargo Release/Simplified Entry(SE), Entry Summary, PGA Integration, and ABI Profiles. Cargo Release/SE will provide the single window for the international trade community with a more automated and modern process that streamlines data requirements, removes paper, and provides for expedited decisions by Federal agencies for imports. Entry Summary processing development focuses on critical system edits or checks that validate the accuracy of the data being submitted to CBP.  PGA Integration continues to build capabilities that allow previously unavailable data to be provided by ACE to PGAs for safety targeting on imports, increasing all agencies' ability to segment risk and focus on those shipments with security, health and safety, and admissibility concerns. ABI Profiles  validate all input and output trade data transmitted to CBP via  trade systems. The new capability will  ensure trade data is routing accurately to the correct trade member.

During this project capabilities will be created for Cargo Release/SE, Entry Summary, PGA Integration, Exports and Manifest. Cargo Release/SE will provide the single window for the international trade community with a more automated and modern process that streamlines data requirements, removes paper, and provides for expedited decisions by Federal agencies for imports. Entry Summary processing development focuses on critical system edits or checks that validate the accuracy of the data being submitted to CBP.  PGA Integration continues to build capabilities that allow previously unavailable data to be provided by ACE to PGAs for safety targeting on imports, increasing all agencies' ability to segment risk and focus on those shipments with security, health and safety, and admissibility concerns. Automated Export System re-engineering effort will incorporate current export processing features in ACE and create a single automated export processing platform for export manifest commodity, and export control and licensing transactions. Manifests will modernize Air and Manifest processing. The ability to integrate Air Manifest with SE and  Cargo Release to correlate manifest bills of lading with entries. The ability to integrate the ATS for screening and targeting Air In-Bond functionality. Truck, Sea, and Rail manifests have already been modernized.

During this project capabilities will be created for Cargo Release/SE, Entry Summary,  Exports, Manifest, and technical platform. Cargo Release/SE will provide the single window for the international trade community with a more automated and modern process that streamlines data requirements, removes paper, and provides for expedited decisions by Federal agencies for imports. Entry Summary processing development focuses on critical system edits or checks that validate the accuracy of the data being submitted to CBP.  PGA Integration continues to build capabilities that allow previously unavailable data to be provided by ACE to PGAs for safety targeting on imports, increasing all agencies' ability to segment risk and focus on those shipments with security, health and safety, and admissibility concerns. Automated Export System re-engineering effort will incorporate current export processing features in ACE and create a single automated export processing platform for export manifest commodity, and export control and licensing transactions. Manifests will modernize Air and Manifest processing. The ability to integrate Air Manifest with SE and  Cargo Release to correlate manifest bills of lading with entries. The ability to integrate the ATS for screening and targeting Air In-Bond functionality. Truck, Sea, and Rail manifests have already been modernized.

By the end of 2012, this project will complete a selected refresh of the most critically outdated desktop computer workstations in USCIS offices nation-wide using FY12 funding. Currently, within USCIS over 38% (8609) of the existing desktop computers in service are over 6-years old. Enterprise Infrastructure Division (EID) within USCIS OIT is responsible for the O&M of the USCIS Global IT Infrastructure.  Inherent in this mission is the management of the Network Operations Center (NOC).  The NOC is the central monitoring, coordinating, remediating and reporting authority for all network incidents, maintenance, and outages for the USCIS infrastructure.  It supports the infrastructure 24 hours a day, 365 days per year.  It provides support to both the USCIS Local and Wide Area Networks (LAN) and (WAN) and also interfaces with and coordinates through the DHS for WAN support.  It further provides applications support for the Data Center Hosting Services through the monitoring of systems and round the clock response to alerts.

Video Services refers to the acquisition, deployment, and ongoing support of technology associated with video conferencing capabilities.  Examples of costs included in video services are servers, workstations, bridges, switches to stage, maintain and operate video systems and all other devices, staff (in house or contracted), and software to manage the same.

Voice Services refers to communication over long distances and typically covers all forms of distance and/or conversion of the original communications.  Examples of costs included in voice services are land line services, telephone devices, VOIP appliances, servers, handsets and software added to a data network to allow voice communications.
KSMS 1.3 contains a series of enhancements that cover multiple areas of KSMS including further streamlined appeals process, additional single shipper features, and better integration with D&B's IM.

KSMS 1.4 contains a series of enhancements that cover multiple areas of KSMS including redesigning the create single shipper page, enhancing the alerts and messages, and cleaning up parts of KSMS to reduce confusion for users.

IACMS 2.5 contains a series of enhancements and defect fixes that will improve the IACMS application.  In particular, the system will be enhanced to allow mass replace association of STAs, improved usability, screen changes to conform with policy changes, improved notification for users, and allow for the addition and management of principals.

IACMS 2.6 focuses on the STA expiration and renewal process.  Enhancements will be built out to include a new STA expiration process.  Once STAs are due to expire, the user will be able to renew their STA.  This release also includes a handful of defect tickets that are primarily related to performance improvements in IACMS.
FAS/CRT 3.10 provides additional management reports and enhances the security audit log. The alterations will enhance the usability and logging capabilities of FAS.
FAS/CRT 4.0 will deploy reports, variance checks, and automated notification to support air carrier reporting. The alterations will improve the notification process within FAS.
This release is primarily a maintenance release.  It will fix bugs and usability issues.
FAS/CRT 3.9 provides bug fixes and recommendations from previous UAT results, including support for air carrier reporting, that will enhance the user capabilities of FAS.

IACMS 2.7 focuses on addressing some key usability issues that arose once IACs were given the ability to renew their STAs. New features include giving the IACs the ability to search for STAs to renew, allowing IACs to 'release' an STA that was already submitted for renewal, and updating the grace period to be a rolling grace period.
The objectives of the IACMS 2.8 release focus on enhancing features related to managing STAs, addressing security vulnerabilities, and an enhanced pagination functionality.

The objectives of the FAS/CRT 4.2 release include the addition of a new query and reporting tool for TSA users and improvements to the usability of the application. The expected outcome of this release is an increase in the ability for TSA Air Cargo to report on data captured by the system and an increase in the overall usability of the system.

The objectives of the FAS/CRT 4.3 release include the addition of improvements to the usability of the application. The expected outcome of this release is an increase in the overall usability of the system.

The objectives of the FAS/CRT 4.4 release include the addition of iimprovements to the usability of the application. The expected outcome of this release is an increase in the overall usability of the system.

The objective of this VAS release is to create required SELC documentation and implement vulnerability assessment reports to report out domain awareness, threat, and vulnerability information for purpose of predicting the consequences of continued vulnerabilities as it relates to terrorist acts across modes of transportation.

The objectives of this project are centered on increasing the usability of the application through modular development and addressing existing defects. The expected outcome is an increase in the overall usability of IACMS.

The objectives of this project focus on a series of enhancements that cover multiple areas of KSMS including deploying additional enhancements to the bulk upload submission process, improved Error handling, and other usability enhancements. The expected outcome of this project is an increase in the usability of the application.
The objectives of this project include the addition of improvements to the usability of the application. The expected outcome of this release is an increase in the overall usability of the system.

The ACRIMe Modernization project is replacing the legacy ACRIMe system with an enterprise-based system, providing access regardless of the users' physical location. ACRIMe Modernization is automating numerous manual processes and providing web-based screens for ICE Agents to access the data used by LESC LESs in making status determinations, rather than having to re-process a subject's criminal and immigration history (as done with the legacy system).

The Status Determination Support project provides modules of functionality to ACRIMe that streamline the processes LESs use to manage ICE issued warrants and lookouts within the FBI's National Crime Information Center (NCIC) and to automate the searching of other systems.

The Automated Threat Prioritization (ATP) project is deploying a web-service that ACRIMe and other systems can call to perform an analysis of a subject's criminal and immigration history. The analysis returns a criminal offense level and a threat to community score that can be used by the calling system to automatically prioritize high-threat subjects.

The Alien Criminal History Entry Screen (ACES) allows ICE agents to enter a subject's information into the Enforcement Integrated Database, returning past criminal history information for the agent to analyze.

The ACRIMe Modernization Maintenance project provides O&M support for the modernized ACRIMe system and its supporting modules, including those developed under the ACRIMe Modernization and Status Determination Support projects.
The Automated Threat Prioritization Maintenance project provides O&M support for the Automated Threat Prioritization system.

The CAII System Enhancements project will provide additional enhancements and functionality for the various CAII components. These include enhancing the NCIC Wants and Warrants Processing component with a new Warrant and Lookout request entry screen, and expanding the full search capability to ICE Agents so they can search DHS and FBI systems from a single integrated screen.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The New Core Program is a multi-phase effort to modernize HUD's core financial and key administrative systems by transitioning the system functions to a shared services environment. New Core's first phase will migrate financial management and administrative functions (budgeting, accounting, finance, reporting, travel and relocation, time and attendance, and procurement) to the Department of Treasury, Bureau of Fiscal Services, Administrative Resource Center's (ARC) shared services platform through multiple releases. New Core's first phase consists of two primary components - Shared Services and HUD Infrastructure. The Shared Services component includes all activities to migrate HUD's financial and administrative functions to ARC, as described above.  This component will be designed based on HUD's requirements and developed by ARC. The HUD Infrastructure component, managed by HUD, includes the establishment of an interface solution to connect HUD to the ARC platform and activities related to HUD's enterprise data warehouse.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The FHA Transformation Initiative's goal is to leverage a modern  information technology platform to better manage and mitigate risk across all of FHA's Insurance Programs.  Specifically, FHA Transformation will enable risk detection and fraud prevention by capturing critical data points at the front-end of the loan life cycle and leveraging the industry standard risk and fraud tools and services, rules-based technology, and transactional controls to minimize exposure to FHA's Insurance Funds.  This will protect consumers and support the housing market by ensuring that underwriting standards are adhered to.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Project Name: Re-engineer Integrated Disbursement Information System (IDIS) To Remove First-In-First-Out (FIFO)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: IDIS manages the fund disbursement rules for thousands of grantees and sub recipients totaling approximately $5 billion annually in program funds. Beginning FY14 IDIS will require a fundamental change to the processing and attribution of grant year funds to individual disbursement events, away from the first-in-first-out (FIFO) method toward funds disbursements confined specifically to the grant year for which an activity is set-up by the grantee. This activity is a Deputy Secretary priority and will ensure IDIS system compliance to Federal Financial Management Improvement Act (FFMIA). This DME activity eliminates CPD's contribution to the qualified opinion for HUD's FY13 Financial Statement.

This effort will assist in capturing accurate property risk in iREMS.

Agency Name: Department of Housing and Urban Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Field Asset Management Division is in need of a Prepayment tracking system that allows Multifamily Hubs and Program Centers to upload PDF documents to Field Asset Management's SharePoint site.  This tracking feature will allow users to better track the number of Prepayment Requests received, the types of mortgage insurance prepaid, and the number of days to complete each request, the number of prepayment requests approved, denied, or cancelled, and provide a centralized place for Multifamily Hubs, Program Centers and Field Asset Management staff to upload and retrieve documents. Capacity limitations affect current or anticipated workload. The existing tracking system used is SharePoint. Since SharePoint cannot handle large amounts of data, more storage capacity is needed within an existing application such as iREMS. In addition to this, due to the reorganization, there is need to be able to seamlessly share data and ensure efficient workflow, assignments and a timely response to stakeholders.

Investment Title: Messaging Services, Email and Remote Connectivity
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The ClassNet Desktop Services Modernization Project (referred to as ClassNet Modernization) is a Global Information Technology Modernization (GITM) sponsored project focusing on building, testing and deploying upgrades to the ClassNet terminal servers overseas, and ClassNet thin clients world-wide.  This project implement and deploy updates to the ClassNet Citrix servers overseas, overseas fat clients, and thin clients world-wide to align the ClassNet system with objectives identified in the DoS IT Strategic Plan (ITSP) for fiscal years 2011-2013.  It is (1) Building, testing and making available Windows Embedded Standard (WES) 7, WES 2009 and HP Zero Client operating system images to 6700 overseas and 6000 domestic thin clients currently using embedded XP (XPe) operating system (XPe reaches End-of-Life in January 12, 2016), (2) Updating physical terminal servers from Windows 2003 to the Windows 2008R2 operating system,  and upgrading server memory and drives, (3) Installing Citrix XenApp 6.5 on terminal servers to support enhanced client monitoring and port security, (4) Integrating the latest PKI hardware and software, (5) Standardizing the baseline image installed on physical and virtual terminal servers (establishing an SOE-S), (6) Standardizing the baseline image presented to all ClassNet end users, (7) Ensuring system assets are under centralized management and configuration control, (8) Designing the system to meet short-term and long-term resource requirements, and (9) Upgrading the overseas fat clients running on the XP OS to the Microsoft Windows 7 image.

The Next Generation of PASS, eServices 2.0, consolidates servers and centralizes data storage to facilitate real time reporting, data sharing and integration by utilizing web services through the Enterprise Service Bus (ESB) and Data Management tools. The Master Reference Database (MRD) is utilized as the source for reference table information.  Centralizing and standardizing databases ensures data consistency and integrity, thus preventing security vulnerabilities and data corruption.  eServices 2.0 will be used by the Department of State staff and other Agencies under Chief of Mission authority at overseas posts.  Centralizing eServices 2.0 guarantees high availability, with redundancy for disaster recovery and serves as the platform or launching pad for all applications that provide service to overseas posts.

The Enterprise Metadata Repository is the centralized repository for the authoritative reference for definition, sources, and use of DoS meta data. The implementation of EMR facilitates re-use of existing data structures, identifies authoritative sorces and stewards of data, shows relationships of data used, and provides end-to-end lineage of data used across DoS.  The EMR can facilitate the implementation of data standards, while highlighting the impact of changes to data, resulting in better understanding of data used throughout DoS.
This project includes multiple minor releases to EDW 2.04.xx to establish functionality around new data points, dashboard enhancements, and software upgrades.

The Master Reference Data (MRD) system provides a central source for the State Department's standard reference data information, such as Org, Fund, Post, Object, Agency and Allotments-. codes. It is designed not only to improve the accuracy, consistency, and completeness of reference data across the department, but also to reduce the effort required to maintain them.

The Ring of Fire Rescaling Project will enhance performance and reduce bottlenecks between the four major domestic data centers and core network components. The integration of these and other initiatives will result in mission, post, and regional enhancements as well as a reduction in the rate of growth of bandwidth costs due to effective deployment of bandwidth use enhancement technologies.

Currently, posts around the world manage their own data backup and storage as outlined in their business continuity/disaster recovery plans.  Several locations are managing local off-shoring for data backup and storage with the use of in-country applications, which have the potential for data loss in the event of a local disaster.  There is no readily available, reliable, or consolidated solution for data off-shoring and the need has been growing with the increased number of posts in high threat areas.  As such, the Data Off-shoring Project was chartered on March 8, 2011 by the Bureau of Information Resource Management (IRM) and Bureaus of Near Eastern Affairs and South and Central Asian Affairs (NEA-SCA) to design and pilot a data off-shoring solution.  NEA-SCA has requested and volunteered to pilot the solution at select posts. The purpose of the Data Off-shoring Project is to design and pilot a solution that will enable the Department of State (DoS) to back up users' core data to a secure remote location in the event of an emergency.  Upon successful completion of the pilots, a separate project may be initiated for a larger scale data off-shoring deployment and transition to Operations and Maintenance (O&M).

The purpose of the Regionalization of ClassNet Services project is to consolidate IT resources and services for DoS's classified network into hub locations. Regionalization of classified services and resources into regional hubs will enable the Department to create greater economies of scale for global IT resources and enable more flexible IT staffing for the Regional Bureaus. This will allow the Department to provide more effective technical and user support at lower total cost, while maintaining strong control over security configurations and aligns with IT Strategic Plan, Goals 4.3: Green IT,  4.4: Life-cycle Management, and  4.5: Cyber Security. The project team will work with the Regional Bureaus and IRM Offices to evaluate the posts and potential hub locations to determine which services and resources could be regionalized. Depending on what is possible given the unique requirements and infrastructure at each post, regionalization could be implemented post-by-post or service-by-service. In support of the DoS' IT Strategic Plan, Goal 5.2: Centralized Shared Services, the long term strategy is to have the Department's ClassNet data and services consolidated into regional hubs within six to eight years, including planning, implementing, and transitioning to operations and maintenance.

In May of 2010, the Department of State (DoS) and U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) commissioned a joint evaluation of alternatives for the consolidation of DoS and USAID overseas IT infrastructure and services into a single, flexible IT platform. This evaluation resulted in the joint DoS/USAID IT Transformation Initiative (ITTI), which would establish a combined IT service model at approximately 70 overseas locations where DoS and USAID have a presence. The transformed IT platform will be known as the Foreign Affairs Network (FAN). Aside from DoS, USAID is the single largest IT consumer at post; transforming the IT infrastructure of these agencies will yield significant cost savings, reduce duplicative services, and increase information sharing.  Following the transformation, this iteration of the FAN will be further leveraged to support collaboration and communication among all Federal entities assigned overseas under Chief of Mission authority.  Upon completion, the FAN, managed by the Department of State will provide IT infrastructure services to USAID at their missions abroad under the ICASS service model.  USAID's current networking will be migrated to a State Department platform including international communications.  USAID local support staff will also be combined with State's under the direction of State IT managers and reduced to the number determined optimal for the combined user base.  Asset ownership (workstations and servers) remain with USAID while operations and management responsibility will transfer to the State Department. However,  USAID's lack of involvement, input and multiple paused resulted transformation completion of only 8 posts for FY12-FY13 duration.

Program Engineering Support includes the GIISST and the ABC Study. The GNSS Intentional Interference and Spoofing Study Team (GIISST) was established by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Satellite Navigation Program Office and Aircraft Certification Service - Avionic Systems Branch (co-sponsors) to study existing threat assessments, relevant studies and data, and develop specific, actionable recommendations for the FAA with regard to technical, political/legal, and operational mitigations for civil aviation GNSS vulnerabilities to intentional interference and spoofing.  The Adjacent Band Capability (ABC) activity is a direct outgrowth of the Light Squared interference analysis. The first phase of the ABC effort is to investigate current susceptibility of aviation equipment to base station and handset LTE signals.

SWIM Governance entails the strategic governance processes development, the Governance Plan Review/Update, definition and implementation of a NAS-wide Service Oriented Architecture (SOA) Center of Excellence (COE).

Standards in the SOA environment are rapidly evolving, and are expected to change between SWIM segments. To accommodate these changes, the SWIM architecture encourages the separation of mission logic components, which implement Air Traffic Management (ATM) services, from information technology (IT) components, which implement standards-based core services. Project Name: First Phase of EDS/FARS Hosting Migration and CDAN Planning
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Modernization of NHTSA legacy IT Investments Electronic Data System (EDS) and Fatality Analysis Reporting System (FARS). DME phase of ModCon will produce Steady State phase called CDAN (Crash Data Acquisition Network). This project includes the initial migration and project planning and mangement as well as identifying alterntives and a recommended implementation plan.

This project was de-scoped to only include the activities of Development Acquisition Planning, Requirements and Database Infrastructure.  All de-scoped activities are now included in the rebaselined Projects described below.

Establish contracts and resources required to initiate and put in place a Project Management framework and structure to fulfill approved design concepts from SELECT Phase. Deliverables within this timeframe include: create Proj Mgmt Plan (PMP), Concept of Operations (CONOPS), create PM SharePoint resource to include a PM Center as central respository for all project documents, decisions, design, etc. Acquisition of Quality Assurance (QA) resources to provide IV&V/QA services during the development cycle. Produce early Data Model (DM) and Variable Repository (VR) designs to provide modernized and consolidated back end for an IT Investment that will host multiple data collection customer projects during the O&M lifecycle.Planning and Design phase also included identification of investment hosting options (Prod/BKP/Test) and producing alternatives analysis on each to make a best determination of final site. Working in coordination with NHTSA OCIO resources to develop an Enterprise strategy for eventual data availability solutions that align with existing agency EA guidelines.

Acquisition of resources for designated COTS (SmartForm) base product for customization to CDAN needs. Prepare and hold what is referred to as a Discovery Session with the target customer to design how the COTS product will function and what level of customization must be developed to produce the main data collection application that will be deployed as the replacement application for legacy application NASSMain which serviced EDS IT Investment customer projects such as NASS/CDS, SCI and CIREN. Discovery Report results produce the Version 1 Initial application development design scheduled for Jan-Jun 2014 through a series of (4) Sprint Releases. Iteration also includes legacy FARS Investment activities in parallel with legacy EDS activities to consolidate FARS data definitions to the CDAN Data Model. FARS migration from vendor site to SFC data center as part of the overall data center reduction goal of CDAN.

Continuation of activities started in Iteration 1 of product development, designing, acquiring and implementing CDAN architecture products/services designated as outputs from project SELECT Phase. Begin CONTROL Phase with SmartForm development and tracking/reporting of EVM. Continue to design, refine and develop tasks and activities to fulfill infrastructure decisions regarding Production and Test Site Hosting (potentially at DOT Southeast Federal Center data center), and Backup/Disaster Recovery Site Hosting (Stennis Data Center). Project resources begin to look at associated primary project tasks to include Quality Assurance/Quality Control (QA/QC) of day-to-day and annual data cycles to ensure CDAN data integrity. Examination and work in partnership with NHTSA OCIO to plan physical as well as data security plans and compliance measures that CDAN must meet.

Updated PMP, Project Governance and Communication Plan (PGCP), Integrated Master Schedule (IMS) updates due. Updated versions of Administrative and internal NHTSA, NCSA and potentially DOT-wide customer tools/resources known as CDAN ToolBox scheduled for initial development, approval. Design and plan for combined CDAN HelpDesk resource that will multiple current HelpDesk resources for all CDAN data collection projects due during this iteration. Version 1.2 of System Security Plan due. Version 3.2 of System Support Documentation due for delivery. Version 1.1 of SmartForm application will be due in Oct 2014, Custom Web Applications for all program customers  use will be defined/designed and resourced. Version 1.1 of the SmartForm application will include additional capabilities beyond those in Version 1, such as front-end data validation and other refinements.  The custom web applications will continue to undergo phased user testing, release acceptance and deployment in line with Agile development principles.  The first version of the Transactional Database will provide the initial capability for data storage after collection. First iteration of the Transaction database is due for testing/acceptance during this timeframe.

CDAN Scope Enhancement Funding to provide resources for (Police Accident Report) PAR management, PAR security solutions development, testing and implementation. Regular updates for PMP, PGCP, IMS. SharePoint PM site enhancements, Agile Story Management, initial acquisition of products/services required for COTS (DeltaV calculation software (WinSmash) and Crash Reconstruction software (ARAS)) and initial procurement of field site data collection equipment. Additional funding to support multi-step plan for providing secure, verifiable access to CDAN federal systems by data collection contract personnel.

Scheduled updates to PM resources PMP, PGCP and IMS. Preparation and finalization of infrastructure/architecture resources for production deployment of FARS/GES data collection project within the CDAN Investment on 1/1/2015. Includes operational status for Production Host environment (SFC) and BKP/DR host environment (Stennis). Version 1 of Mobile Device Management (MDM) Plan due, which will outline support necessary to ensure asset, access and content security for all mobile devices (aka tablets) acquired and used across CDAN projects. Version 3 of System Requirements Specifications due as well as Version 4 of System Support Documentation. The FARS MDE (Micro Data Entry) main data collection application will be finalized and deployed to the FARS/GES CDAN environment, and this app that will handle input processing of state-based FARS system data. Design/Plan/Development cycle continues for the CDAN Operational Data Store (ODS), which maintains validated data from all CDAN data collection projects, Data Mart which will provide NHTSA enterprise-wide customers with access to detailed CDAN project data, and Centralized Data Warehouse which is a NHTSA-sponsored, public-facing data access portal.

Refinement and implementation coordination with primary customer to conduct live field test of modernized solution (Mar-May, tentative). Continue to refine the BKP/Replication of data methods/services and Data Mart resources. Initial versions of Operational Reporting System (Knowledge Center), NCSA Analytics Center (NAC) and NCSA Data Services scheduled as deliverables. Continued development, testing and refinement of Centralized Data Warehouse resources to include published data extracts for public consumption.

Final Development/Control tasks and activities in pre-Production preparation that includes: SmartForm/Tablet deployment, HelpDesk Resources, IT support in set up, and approval process of field site locations, Data Mart, Knowledge Center, Analytics Center and Data Warehouse (to include Corporate Information Factory). Conduct test/acceptance of technical as well as user/customer non-technical documentation. Provide IT support where needed for pre-Production training sessions for primary CDAN users (data collectors). Perform security audit prior to production release to include (ATO, C&A) and operational readiness of federal system access security measures.

Finalize transition from DME to O&M status for CDAN IT Investment. Verify operational success of Prod/BKP/Test environments, ensure projected workflow and data flow are performing as planned, ensure all documentation is in place, verified and accepted, conduct DME retrospective. Begin coordination with O&M resource on legacy sunset and impact on CDAN.

Project Name: NextGen R&D Flexibility in Terminal Environment Solution Set (FLEXs)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: NextGen R&D Flexibility in Terminal Environment (FLEXs) concentrates on improvements in the access, situational awareness, and separation services at airports of all sizes.

Project Name: NextGen R&D Arrivals/Departures at High Density Airport Solution Set (HDs)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: NextGen R&D Arrivals/Departures at High Density Airport (HDs) solution set addresses improving the use of available capacity at airports with large numbers of operations that have multiple runways and airspace in close proximity to other airports.

Project Name: NextGen R&D Reduce Weather Impact Solution Set (RWIs)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: NextGen R&D Reduce Weather Impact (RWIs) provides improvements including accurate, consistent, and integrated weather information to air traffic management specialists, other air traffic control facilities, airline flight operations centers (FOC), & the flight deck.

Project Name: NextGen R&D Trajectory Based Operations Solution Set (TBOs)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: NextGen R&D Trajectory Based Operations (TBOs) will use separation automation to create the first steps toward a future in which aircraft will be assigned to fly negotiated trajectories, allowing airspace to be used more efficiently.

Project Name: NextGen R&D Collaborative Air Traffic Management  (CATM)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The NextGen R&D Collaborative Air Traffic Management  (CATM) coordinates flight and flow decision-making by flight planners and FAA traffic managers to improve overall efficiency, provide greater flexibility to flight planners, and make the best use of available airspace and airport capacity.

Project Name: NextGen R&D Improved Multiple Runway Operations (IMRO)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The NextGen R&D Improved Multiple Runway Operations (IMRO) supports improving approach and departure operations to closely spaced, parallel, converging, and intersecting runways.

The NextGen R&D Improved Surface Operations (Surf-Op) supports improving safety, efficiency, and flexibility by implementing new capabilities for both pilots and the Air Navigation Service Provider to improve surface situational awareness and automation to support surface operations.

Project Name: NextGen R&D On Demand NAS Information (NAS-Info)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The NextGen R&D On Demand NAS Information (NAS-Info) will implement programs and processes to ensure that NAS and aeronautical information are consistent across applications and locations, and are available to authorized subscribers and equipped aircraft.

The NextGen R&D Performance Based Navigation (PBN) provides a framework for defining performance requirements in navigation specifications that contain detailed aircraft and operator/pilot requirements, and provides a basis for the design and implementation of air traffic routes and instrument procedures and also can support airspace design requirements.

The NextGen R&D Separation Management (Sep-Man) supports enhancements to the existing Air Traffic Separation Management systems and provides controllers with additional tools and procedures to manage aircraft in a mixed environment of varying navigation equipment and wake performance capabilities.

Project Name: NextGen R&D Time Based Flow Manager (TBFM)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The NextGen R&D Time Based Flow Manager (TBFM) leverages the Traffic Management Advisor (TMA) decision-support tool to enable aircraft to maintain spacing interval behind preceding aircraft, further improving capacity, flight efficiency, and reducing fuel burn.

HR Connect is the core human resource system of the HR Connect Program Office (HRCPO), a shared services center HR service provider within the U.S. Department of Treasury.  The HR Connect application is the foundation of HRCPO's comprehensive suite of solutions and is rapidly becoming the gold standard among federal HR Line of Business (LOB) providers.HR practitioners, managers and employees use HR Connect (HRC) to perform a wide array of transactions at various stages of an employee's life cycle. HR practitioners use HR Connect to manage human capital and better utilize organizational data for strategic decision making. The system's paperless personnel actions electronically route actions for approval, greatly reducing processing time and the human error associated with manual processing.  Using one of the self-service components of Treasury SSC such as InService, managers can produce recruitment requests as well as requests for personnel actions, such as to promote and award employees.  Managers can also view reports and conduct a range of other  to build, sustain, and manage their team. Employees can make changes to their personal information, view information about their job and benefits, and report their time. As a result, HR practitioners, managers, and employees are partially relieved of cumbersome paperwork and are better able to participate in supporting their agencies' strategic objectives.  The U.S. Department of Commerce is in the process of consolidating its HR service centers by modeling its business processes within HR Connect and migrating HR data from its seven internal HR servicing bureaus into HR Connect.  They, along with our many other customers, recognize that, in addition to saving time and reducing cost, HR practitioners will be able to spend more time on strategic activities that help meet their agencies' core objectives.  HRCPO systems' robust security ensures the confidentiality, integrity and availability of customer data.  Aside from the core HR connect product, the Department of Commerce will also be leveraging our Workforce Analytics product, with plans to integrate EODS in the near future.

IMF Output analyzes, reformats and extracts taxpayer data received from IMF Posting & Analysis processing to Refunds, Notices, Transcripts, Unpostables, Recap and IDRS processing.  The Refund data is sent to Austin Regional Operating Center (AROC); Notice data is passed to NRPS processing; Transcripts are sent to the Service Centers for printing; Recap reports are sent to the Service Centers; and data extracted for IDRS is sent to the Service Centers.

IMFOL is the Individual Master File On-Line project.  IMFOL is part of the Corporate Files ON-Line (CFOL) system and is used primarily to display tax account information on individual taxpayers to IDRS users.  The database and software provide interfaces to other projects such as ENTCK, National Account Profile/On-Line Entity (NAP/OLE), and Telephone Routing Interactive System (TRIS).  The system is hosted on ECC-MTB's IBM mainframe computer using Customer Information Control System (CICS) as a transaction processor.  The database structure for IMFOL is through the Integrated Data Retrieval System/Security and Communications System (IDRS/SACS) telecommunication and security network. All IMFO programs are written in Assembler Language, COBOL, CICS and execute on the IBM Mainframe at ECC-MTB.

IMFDIF is a mathematical technique used to pre-classify and identify a return's high audit potential.  All individual returns are DIF scored but only those above the cut-off are placed onto inventories and made available to Examination field personnel for selection.  Returns can either be selected specifically via a TC424 or bulk ordered via an ordering system.  These accounts provide significant workload for field Examination personnel.

Combine the IRS legacy Personal Identification Number (PIN) solutions for individual taxpayer filing (IMF) into a consolidated solution for 2014 and future years.  The eventual goal is to have one PIN for individual taxpayers in 2015 and beyond to facilitate electronic tax return filing (e-File) and to protect tax payer accounts against identity theft.The aim of this solution is to drive taxpayers to get a legacy Identity Protection (IP) PIN (proposed new name Taxpayer Filing Authentication Certificate [TFAC]) to protect their accounts and to facilitate e-Filing.  In order to receive a TFAC a taxpayer would have authenticate using the IRS e-Authentication (e-Auth) solution that leverage third-party out-of-wallet (OOW) data.  The legacy e-File PIN (EFP) would only be issued to taxpayers that cannot authentication with e-Auth (but can authenticate with legacy methods) to e-File.  Taxpayers issued a legacy e-File PIN would be subject to additional filters and reviews when they file their tax returns.

Project Name: Integrated Data Retrieval System (IDRS) - Filing Season 2012
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Development for legislatively mandated tax law changes (for example, portions of Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act) and customer requested modernization and enhancement (for example, accelerate processing cycle)  * The Integrated Data Retrieval System (IDRS) is an IRS mission critical system consisting of databases and subsystems supporting IRS employees working active tax cases. It manages data retrieved from the Tax Master Files allowing IRS employees to take specific actions on taxpayer account issues, track status and post updates back to the Master Files. It provides for systemic review of case status, alleviating staffing needs and providing consistency in case control. Actions taken via IDRS include notice issuance, installment agreement processing, offers in compromise, adjustment processing, penalty and interest computations and explanations, credit and debit transfers within an account or other related accounts and research of taxpayer accounts for problem resolution of taxpayer inquiries.

The GWA/TRS Project will provide the functionality to enter Classification Key (C-Key) for check processing to support Government Wide accounting implementation in OTCnet project. Providing the information at detail check level will be mandatory for Agencies that are marked as GWA Reporter.  The release includes sending the information to TRS for the first time for check processing using XML Schema v4.6. Deposit processing side of OTCnet transmission to TRS will also be revised to use XML v4.6 schema. Interface specifications will be updated and tested for 3 interfaces including DECA, IRS and DDS systems.

Corrections and Adjustments project will provide the functionality to process Corrections and Adjustments in OTCnet. Corrections and Adjustments for checks will be processed from Debit Gateway to OTCnet and will be reported to TRS. For deposit processing, a user interface will be designed to enter the information into OTCnet and then transmit the information to TRS. Following the scope discussions, this project was cancelled in Feb. 2012.

This project has been postponed to a later date due to re-prioritization. The project was planned to provide dynamic split functionality to agencies for check processing and transmitting the data to TRS and the Central Accounting and Reporting System (CARS).  Agencies have expressed the need to be able to enter C-Key information at summary level for end of day processing for checks.  In the absence of the dynamic split functionality in OTCnet, agencies will have to use bulk reclassification process in GWA which will require agencies to reconcile between two different systems.

Straight through Processing (STP) is a Treasury mandate to provide immediate recording of transactions and near real-time information for reconciliation and management of the Treasury's General Account (TGA) structure. The OTCnet STP implementation will be in two different segments due to immediate and long-term needs. The first implementation of STP in near term will require processing the appropriate Treasury RTNs for checks and deposit processing, processing a new Treasury RTN for Non-Appropriated Funds (NAF), voucher date change and sending it to Collections Information Repository (CIR).  The implementation will be closely coordinated with the Debit Gateway and CIR.  For commercial deposits, a new Treasury RTN will be defined for cash concentration and processed through CIR to Treasury Cash Management System (TCMS). The second implementation of STP will include processing of Adjustment/Correction and Rescinds (ACRs) for checks,, using XML 4.6 schema as standard interface and processing the of end-of-day file from Debit Gateway.

The Archive and Architecture Phase 1 will introduce a check transactional data archival process to improve OTCnet application performance and adhere to Fiscal Service' Data Retention Requirements.  Architecture Phase 1 will include breaking up operational  Online Transaction Processing (OLTP) database and the Archive database into two databases and defining an archive process.  The operational database will hold 18 months of current financial transactions and the archive database containing all historical information.  A new archive process will be defined to move data from operational database to the archive database. Modifications will be made for check search functionality and reports .  Additional architectural changes include converting batch jobs from Hibernate to Spring Batch framework. During phase 1, the archiving process will be limited to check processing only.  Archiving Phase 2 will include expanding archiving to deposit processing and adding additional reports from archive data.  Also, Hibernate optimization will be completed to move away from JBPM and use Spring Batch Framework where inefficiencies exist.
A place holder planning project to Replan Dynamic TAS that has been postponed in 2013 to provide summary level classfication information for check processing.

The Dynamic Split TAS implementation will support the capture of multiple accounting code classifications at the batch level (summary level classification) and the individual check level (item level classification) in both online and offline applications.

A system rewrite of TAAPS will begin in October 2011 with the first phase being define and documentation.  The rewrite may improve auction screens, reports, interfaces, or infrastructure to provide timely, accurate, and informative qualitative/quantitative analysis of Treasury Auctions.  Phase two will be the development phase and move towards the implementation process of the rewrite. Planned implementation of 9/30/2013.

In 2011, Treasury conducted 269 marketable security auctions to borrow the monies needed to fund the United States Government. The auction process must work flawlessly, remain absolutely secure, and operate without service disruptions which could erode public confidence and increase taxpayer costs for debt service. The Treasury Automated Auction Processing System (TAAPS) application and infrastructure have been in production for four years and in development for two years prior to that. In order to stay current with changes in technology, it is prudent to examine various components of the auction process to analyze the validity and adequacy of the utilized technology, application and infrastructure.  The business process components being analyzed have been organized into 8 areas of focus:1. Infrastructure & Security2. Credential Management3. Operational Efficiencies4. Internal Staff Recommendations5. External Participant Feedback6. Data Analytics7. Customer Relationship Management8. Institutional Website Revamp.

FIT recently completed a blueprint for financial management shared services.  The blueprint recommends a shared service approach whereby all Federal agencies migrate to one of several designated Federal and private financial management shared service providers (SSP) that offer, at a minimum, a common set of financial management services and products.  Further, the approach includes a lifecycle approval step where FIT reviews and compares an agency's migration proposal to the common services and products to verify the following:  (1) the agency's needs align with the common services and products; (2) the agency can offer support (e.g., regulatory, statutory) for any needs beyond the common services and products; and (3) any verified Services and Products gaps can be satisfied by one of the designated SSPs.  Once an agency has an acceptable modernization plan, it will begin a brief discovery phase with an SSP process whereby both organizations must agree that the services and products offered by the SSP satisfy the needs of the agency.

FIT has developed a series of financial management measures (e.g., price per invoice, on-time payments, discounts and interest paid) to capture the price and performance of a number of financial management processes (e.g., procure-to-pay, bill-to-collect) provided by Federal SSPs.  FIT captures and aggregates the measures reported by the SSPs in a reporting tool (or benchmarking tool) that aggregates the information as a government-wide benchmark.  FIT, Federal SSPs, and Federal agencies can use the benchmarking tool to compare the cost and performance of the Federal agencies financial management activities to the price and performance of the Federal SSPs.  The benchmarking tool is a web-based application with defined metrics based on seven financial management end-to-end business processes, including Procure-to-Pay and Bill-to-Collect.  The metrics are based on the price and performance of the aligned business processes of the Federal SSPs.  Examples of the metrics include price per invoice, statement of differences, on- time payments, discounts and interest paid.

This will help Veterans get the benefits they deserve and contribute to reducing the claims backlog..

Project Name: Access Received Closer To Home (ARCH) Automated Eligibility Determination
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Veterans' Mental Health And Other Care Improvements Act Of 2008, Section 403, Public Law 110-387 mandates that the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) conduct a pilot program over three years for contract care of eligible Veterans in selected Veterans Integrated Service Networks (VISNs). In response to this mandate, The Office of Policy Analysis within the Office of the Assistant Deputy Under Secretary for Health for Policy and Planning (ADUSH/PP), which is responsible for implementing this pilot, established a New Service Request(NSR)entitled Project Access Received Closer to Home (ARCH) Automated Eligibility Determination. A Business Requirements Document describing the business case and desired functionality for this NSR was signed by business owners on December 1, 2010. The Enhancing Veteran Experience and Access to Healthcare (EVEAH) Operating Plan for Fiscal Year (FY) 11-13 reflects this mandate and further supports action on the NSR. IT Patient Safety also evaluated this request and suggested that it be considered mandatory. The pilot program is scheduled for implementation between the second and third quarters of FY11.

The Home Telehealth programisputting medical devices in patient homes to improve the quality of care and standard of living for veteransbyreducing hospital admissions, clinic visits and emergency room attendances. HT programs are targeted at the 2-3% of patients who utilize 30% of costs and are frequent clinic attendees and require urgent hospital admissions.HT assists patients that are unable to access traditional VA medicalfacilities due toproximity issuesand/or disabilities. The HT program aims to improve care for patients withchronic conditions that can benefit from more frequent monitoring. The overall benefits are better level health with fewer emergencies, happier patients, and lower costs.

This project is to provide continued support for the national implementation of VHAs teleradiology informatics system. This support includes 1)Delivery of VistA Radiology software enhancements that improve the accuracy of data transmitted between the National Teleradiology Program (NTP) and the local sites, 2)Setup of access to a more robust test environment for end-to-end testing of NTP VistA Enhancements, and 3)Provide VistA support to customers of NTP for VAMCs as they activate NTP Services. A national teleradiology system makes more efficient use of radiologists by redistributing work, pooling on-call duties, and assigning studies to specialists.

Provide enhancements for Store and Forward Telemedicine functionality using the VistA Imaging infrastructure and TeleReader client to include improving telemedicine capabilities and specialty support (such as Telepathology and Home Wound Care).

The purpose of the Veterans Health Affairs (VHA) National Teleradiology Program (NTP) is to provide convenient and cost effective radiologic image interpretation service for VA Medical Centers. Due to the 24x7x356 mission critical operation of the National Teleradiology Program (NTP), there is a requirement to have redundant, fault tolerant LAN and WAN connections withinreading centers and from the reading centers to the Sacramento RDPC where the NTP houses its central servers.

Clinical Video Teleconferencing (CVT) - Based upon VAs existing telehealth capabilities and work recently undertaken, the vision of senior VA leadership is of a transformational increase in VAs Telehealth capacity nationally. This transformational increase will increase VA Telehealth capacity at the end of FY2013 over end-of-year FY2012 levels by 100% for CVT programs (50% annually).The business need is for the development of a national scheduling system to support CVT to ensure that health care providers, locations, and equipment at both ends of the telehealth visit are all coordinated with the patient across different VeteransInformation Systems Technology Architecture(VistA) scheduling systems and to provide for workload capture.

Based upon  the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA)'s existing Telehealth capabilities and work undertaken in the Fiscal Year (FY) 2010 timeframe, the vision of   senior VA leadership is of a transformational increase in VA's Telehealth capacity nationally. This transformational increase will increase VA Telehealth capacity at the end of FY2012 over end-of-year FY2010 levels by 100% for care coordination home telehealth (CCHT) programs (50% annually)..

The Work Study Management System (WSMS) processes and manages veteran Work Study student applications, contracts, and time records. It is used by Regional Processing Offices (RPOs) to process these claims. The system facilitates the processing of benefits claims from veterans enrolled in work study programs by improving the efficiency, accuracy and management of claims for benefits.

TIMS is a critical application that supports the processing of Education benefits that fall under Chapter 30, 32, 33, 35, 1606 and 1607. TIMS contains electronic claims folders and provides electronic storage, retrieval and workflow processing for all VA education benefits claims.

The Automate GI Bill Program assists the veteran and other beneficiaries by improving the quality and accessibility of the Post 9/11 GI Bill educational benefit. Release 5 will improve automation and self-service functionality within the long-term solution (LTS) as well as integration with other VA systems. Additionally, it will include support for the transition of software licenses back to the VA.

Project Name: Automate GI Bill Long-Term Solution Development
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Automate GI Bill Program assists the veteran and other beneficiaries by improving the quality and accessibility of the Post 9/11 GI Bill educational benefit. The Chapter 33 Automation Deployment 1 will provide initial automation capability likely focusing on a subset of supplemental claims processing and will include additional functional stories depending on available deployment capacity.

The Veterans Retraining Assistance Program (VRAP) was signed into law on November 21, 2011, as part of the Veterans Opportunityto Work (VOW) to Hire Heroes Act of 2011 (PL 112-56). This program directs the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), in cooperation with the Department of Labor (DOL), to pay the chapter 30 full-time rate to unemployed eligible Veterans.Qualified Veterans, between the ages of 35 and 60,may receive up to 12 months worth of training benefits in pursuit ofa high demand occupation (as deemed bythe DOL). The project is to develop the necessary interagency agreements; claims processing procedures; IT support and procedures; and essential reports required to successfully implement VRAP in cooperation withthe DOL.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: In FY11, using agile development methodology, the Veterans Benefits Management System (VBMS) created a software product that would improve efficiency in the Veterans claims management process. Phase 1 delivered a prototype to prove the concept of smart scanning, an electronic folder of images to replace the paper folder and web services application to establish a claim in the system. In Phase 2, the application will be changed from a prototype to an enterprise-capable application with the necessary supporting infrastructure to provide the foundational components for a nationally deployed paperless solution. VBMS is a business transformation initiative designed to reduce the processing time of a Veteran claim to 125 days. VBMS will increase efficiency, improve quality, reduce the backlog of pending claims, and ensure the timely and accurate delivery of disability benefits paid each month to Veterans and their beneficiaries.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Phase 4 in FY12 will be the deployment of the Veterans Benefits Management System (VBMS) software solution on a national scale. National deployment will integrate new and improved business processes through a software solution that is Web based and has the functionality to establish a claim and the paperless folder in VBMS. National Deployment will take place in phases throughout calendar year 2012 and 2013 to support and fulfill goal of an improved business process. VBMS is a business transformation initiative designed to reduce the processing time of a Veteran claim to 125 days from the current level of 161 days. VBMS will increase efficiency, improve quality, reduce the backlog of pending claims, and ensure the timely and accurate delivery of disability benefits paid each month to Veterans and their beneficiaries.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: VBMS Phase 3 will integrate new and improved business processes with the paperless claims software solution that was developed, refined and validated during the pilot of the VBMS Virtual Regional Office (VRO) and the two previous phases. Phase 3 will be deployed in 2012 and will be used to validate the VBMS technology with increased volume of users and claims and improved business processes to a larger scale of end users throughout the Veterans Benefits Administration (VBA) Regional Offices. This effort will increase the efficiency of claims processing and ensure timely and accurate deliver of disability benefits paid each month to Veterans and their beneficiaries. The development for this effort is to be completed through an interagency agreement and funding is awarded during planning for the duration of the effort.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Centeralized Administrative Accounting Transactions System (CAATS) is a web-based,data-centric application which is based around the ability to create, submit and track multiple types of accounting transactions through a workflow process. This system will enable the VA tofullyreplace themanual processcurrently being used.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: In support of the Veterans Benefits Management Assistance Program (VBMAP) and C&P Record Interchange (CAPRI), thisprocurement requestwill acquiredeveloper support services, hardware and software. The procurment is to fund modifications to existingIT systems (hardware/software)that alignwith VBAs vision tointroduce enhanced technologiesthat facilitate end-to-end claims processing in a paperless environment.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: Veterans Benefits Administrations (VBA) Fiduciary Program oversees VA benefits paid to beneficiaries who are incapable of managing their funds. The Fiduciary Beneficiary System Replacement (FBSR) project will benefit the Veteran by providing FBS staff with an improved ability to execute, manage, monitor and report on the status of the fiduciary business process.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Project Name: Centralized Administrative Accounting Transaction System (CAATS) Phase II
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Centralized Administrative Accounting Transactions System (CAATS) Phase II is a web-based, data-centric application which is based around the ability to create, submit and track multiple types of accounting transaction through a worklfow process. This system will enable the VA to fully replace the manual process.

Investment Title: Benefits 21st Century Paperless Delivery of Veterans Benefits
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: National Deployment (Phase 5) planning and development in FY14 will integrate new and improved business processes with a software solution that was developed, refined and validated during the Virtual Regional Office (VRO) and the three previous phases. National Deployment was initiated in CY12 and will be used to implement the Veteran Benefits Management System (VBMS) technology and improved business processes throughout the Veterans Benefits Administration (VBA) regional offices..

The Agent Orange (Fast Track) FY10 requestwas used to fund contractor support to design and develop an automated claims system called Fast Track for processing newly added Agent Orange (AO) Presumptive conditions, as well as any other new AO Presumptive conditions that may be added during the life of the contract using an Agile development methodology. The contractor has developed a suite of web-enabled claims forms that allows claimants to electronically download and, at the claimants option, electronically submit complete claims for Vietnam era service connection. Also for the first time in VA, the claimant and their provider(s) are now able to upload supporting medical evidence for the presumptive conditions in the form of Disability Benefits Questionnaires (DBQs) that become a part of the electronic claim. The initial development effort was funded out of the VA Innovations Initiatives (VAi2), and the FY11 and FY12 enhancement work is funded out of OI&T/Product Development as part of the President's budget.

CWINRS is a case management application re-engineered and enhanced from a field developed application for the Vocational Rehabilitation and Employment (VR&E) offices in the Department of Veterans Affairs Regional Offices (VAROs). CWINRS provides VARO staff, outstation staff, contractors, and others with a means of maintaining accurate information for service-connected disabled veterans participating in the VR&E program. CWINRS utilizes the Veterans Benefits Administrations (VBAs) Corporate database to maintain participant information and interfaces with VBAs BDN and VA Financial Management System (FMS) to process payment and accounting transactions.The project is to remove the CWINRS Application dependency on the legacy VBA BDN and use the newer Financial Accounting System for payment and accounting processing.

The Vocational Rehabilitation & Employment Quality Assurance Web Application (VR&E QA Web) project was developed under OI&Ts Process Modeling Center of Excellence (PMCE) as a pilot project to improve business process s and support VR&Es Quality Assurance (QA) program. This project is designed to complete the work started under the PMCE and provide for future functionality enhancements to VR&E QA program.

Project Name: St Paul Rules Based Claims Processing Pilot
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The project is aligned with VAs overall goal to reduce backlog. The Rules-based Processing System (RBPS) is expected to reduce the processing time and eliminate decision variance by building the processing rules and guidance into the automated business rule system. Also, the project decreases the claims backlog and frees staff processing hours which can then be realigned to claims requiring manual intervention.

The Rules Based Processing System (RBPS) initiative will enhance rules-based processing of identified dependency claims, including award creation, denials, removals, automatic payment adjustments and letter generation. This System was piloted at the St. Paul Regional office. Approximately 30% of claims met the criteria for automatic processing. Of these claims, RBPS dramatically improved the processing times going from an average of 150 days to 5 days. This Project expects to increase this to 50% of claims being automatically processed.

At this time, FOCAS does not contain the functionality to provide the Business Needs mentioned in the BRD. These need are product of a UAT testing. Additionally, the SME's also discovered an issue relating to Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and suggested an enhancement that will assist in the protection of this information. There are no alternatives to the facilitation of these Business Needs other than implementation of the requested additions to the FOCAS. The implementation of Enhancements to FOCAS Application will provide value to the customer by increasing the overall accuracy and efficiency of FOCAS claims processing.  .

$300K DME will provide development, test, and deployment support for a redesign of an existing database that funnels information from Treasury to / from VA mainframe regarding beneficiary payments, including two incremental releases, a prototype RATS 1.0 and a releasable version RATS 1.1.  $50K marginal sustainment will sustain the application from the fielding of the app in late FY14 to end of FY14.

Project Name: Centralized Administrative Accounting Transaction System (CAATS) Phase III
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: CAATS objectives/expected outcomes are to improve financial controls and to determine more efficient and effective methodology to streamline and reduce the manual input required by VBA regional offices, which will produce electronic transmission of transaction data that will feed into VA's accounting system. Achieving this outcome will reduce manual processing time and reduce training time. .

VETSNET Release 13 will be application changes required to support the final conversion of Compensation and Pension records from the Benefits Delivery Network to the Veterans Benefit Administration Corporate Database. VETSNET will fix any defects identified with the previous release and deliver new functionality such as Consolidated Payees (Multiple Payments going to a fiduciary), address dairy issues for periodic review of cases as necessary and continue web service development; also Phase 2 of Treasurys Debit Card Program (no more paper checks).

The primary objective for the SEP 2012 release is to allow for an October conversion of remaining BDN data. VETSNET will also expand support of Vocational Rehabilitation Benefits (CH31) and provide enhancements for Personal Funds of Patients (PFOP) and Loan Guaranty(LGY).

VETSNET Release 15 will support the final conversion of records from the legacy system to the new modern payment system for benefits: Burial and Accrued Benefit Payments and continue to support the development of web services for internal and external customers as well as the public at large to provide secure online web interfaces (such as eBenifts.va.gov allowing veterans to apply for benefits online).

Enhancements and ongoing support to VBA's primary application set and single payment engine.  Financial Accounting System (FAS) has no immediate replacement or sunsetting plan, and is currently being expanded in scope to allow for migration of VRE and Education benefits currently paid through BDN.  In addition, FAS requires support to react to the effects of initiatives from various external entities, the Debt Management Center (DMC), the Office of Management and Budget (OMB), the US Department of the Treasury, and ongoing changes implemented by Congress all have items currently in process that will affect payments to our Veterans, and ultimately the FAS engine.   FAS is and will remain for the foreseeable future the payment system for all transformational applications including VBMS and the VRM applications.  Continued FAS development is essential to ensuring that investments in other transformational systems will result in accurate payments to Veterans and Beneficiaries.  Additionally, to ensure proper payments are made to Veterans and Beneficiaries, other VETSNET applications will be necessary until they are sunsetted by their respective replacement VBMS apps. .

The VA Talent Management System (TMS) is a web-based software application (Vendor: Plateau LTD) used to plan, implement, and assess a specific learning process. Typically, a learning management system (LMS) such as TMS provides an instructor with a way to create and deliver content, monitor student participation, and assess student performance. The TMS Enhancements will enable the functions for talent management, recruitment and on-boarding, goal-setting, performance management, assessments, and career and succession planning. This work began in FY11 and will complete in FY12.

Project Name: Human Resources Information System (HRIS) Shared Service Center (SSC)
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: HRIS SSC is a Human Resource (HR)  Information Technology (IT) capability consolidating HR IT System and services to provide core (personnel action processing; benefits and compensation management) HR related functions. HRIS SSC will replace Personnel and Accounting Integrated Data (PAID) which is a 45-year old COBAL-based system at the end of its life span. This project will improve efficiency and effectiveness of HR processes by acquiring a State-of-the-Art, 21st century solution from an approved HR shared service center provider, migrate to a modern, state-of-the-art system that will support current and future HR systems, business processes and data exchange and shift focus from administrative processing to customer service and strategic planning..

Automation (WebHR) of internal Human Resource Services which may interface with the Shared Service Center (SSC) in accordance with Federally mandated Human Resource Line of Business (HR LOB) Initiative. The identified goal for this effort is to expand and convert two existing applications (WebHR and HealthCare Retention, Recruitment Education and Scholarship) into the WebHR portal primarily supporting services and products for the workforce, human resources, and talent management areas.

Project Name: Equal Employment Opportunity-Alternate Dispute Resolution (EEO-ADR) Dashboard
Objectives / Expected Outcomes: The Office of Resolution Management has a need to roll out an Equal Employment Opportunity/Alternate Dispute Resolution dashboard system that will interface with the CATS data source (Complaint Automated Tracking System) and ADR tracker in order to provide a national VA-wide solution.
